properties.Name: FeedstockType
properties.Description:
The type of feedstock.

Ex:
FRACTIONATION PROCESS:
Atmospheric distillation <- Desalted crude oil
Vacuum distillation <- Gas oil, lube stock, residual

CONVERSION PROCESSES - DECOMPOSITION:
Catalytic cracking <- Gas oil, coke distillate
Coking <- Gas oil, coke distillate
Hydro-cracking <- Gas oil, cracked oil, residual
Hydrogen steam reforming <- Desulfurized gas, O2, steam
Steam cracking  <- Heavy fuel/distillate
Visbreaking  (Reduce viscosity) -> Distillate, tar

CONVERSION PROCESSES - UNIFICATION:
Alkylation  (Unite olefins & isoparaffins) -> Iso-octane (alkylate)
Grease compounding <- Lube oil, fatty acid, alky metal
Polymerizing <- Cracker olefins

CONVERSION PROCESSES - ALTERATION OR REARRANGEMENT:
Catalytic reforming <- Coker/hydro-cracker naphtha
Isomerization <- Butane, pentane, hexane

TREATMENT PROCESSES:
Amine treating <- Sour gas, HCs w/CO2 & H2S
Desalting <- Crude oil
Drying & sweetening <- Liq Hcs, LPG, alky feedstock
Furfural extraction <- Cycle oils & lube feed- stocks
Hydrodesulfurization <- High-sulfur residual/gas oil
Hydrotreating <- Residuals, cracked HC's
Phenol extraction <- Lube oil base stocks
Solvent deasphalting <- Vacuum tower residual, propane
Solvent dewaxing <- Vacuum tower lube oils
Solvent extraction <- Gas oil, reformate, distillate
Sweetening <- Untreated distillate/gasoline

CHEMICAL PROCESSES:
Ex
Propene
Natural Gas
Water
Ethylene
1-butene
1-hexene
Vinylic Comonomers
Hexene
Nitrogen

Biomass/ Fuelwood
Biomass/ Pellets
Biomass/ Charcoal

Biomass/ Black Liquor
Biomass/ Bioethanol from crops
Biomass/ Biodiesel from crops
Biomass/ Biogas from crops/animals
Biomass/ Municipal waste

Note:
Propylene may be copolymerized with a range of other olefins, such as ethylene and oc-olefins (1-butene, 1-hexene, etc.). 
The other olefins are termed comonomers and are incorporated into the growing polymer chain.

OTHER

Ex:
Natural Gas (methanol, ammonia, hydrogen)  
Naphtha (methanol, ammonia, hydrogen)
Sour Gas
Rich Gas
Raw Natural Gas
Wet Gas

Note:
The type of feedstock depends on the process.
Natural Gas is a feedstock to product ammonia.
Natural Gas is the product produced in other processes.

Sour Gas 
Gas containing a high level of Carbon Dioxide or Hydrogen Sulfide, which are corrosive in the presence of water. They may therefore require drying or removal to preserve the pipeline. 

Rich Gas 
Rich gas is gas with relatively large quantities of heavier fractions in its composition (typically up to about 15%) and thus of high Calorific Value. Also known as Wet Gas.

Raw Natural Gas 
Natural gas still containing impurities and unwanted substances, such as water, nitrogen, carbon dioxide, hydrogen sulfide gas and helium. 

Wet Gas 
Natural gas containing condensable Hydrocarbons
